 the volume draws portraits of the key actors in the federalist movement – including political leaders, intellectuals, academics, activists, and spokespersons for pressure groups – comparing their various outlooks, interventions, and values, and examining the ties that bind these actors to the sense of nationalism that emerged during Quebec’s Quiet Revolution. Taking a multidisciplinary approach, Contemporary Federalist Thought in Quebec casts new light on the continuing debate surrounding Quebec’s place in Canada and gives nuance to what is traditionally conceived as a rigid opposition between sovereigntists and federalists in the province.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aFederal governmentzQuébec (Province)xHistory. 0aPolitical sciencezQuébec (Province)xHistoryy20th century. 0aPolitical sciencezQuébec (Province)xHistoryy21st century. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / World / Canadian.2bisacsh  aCanada.  acanadian.  aconstitution.  aculture.  afederalism.  agroups.  ahistory.  aintellectuals.  anationalism.  apoliticians.  apolitics.  apressure.  areferendum.  aschools.  asupreme court.1 aBaker, Mary, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBinette, Amélie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoily, Frédéric, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrousseau Desaulniers, Antoine, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBurelle, André, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarlos, Jean-Philippe, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDesaulniers, Antoine Brousseau, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDorais, François-Olivier, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/